               />
              </div>
              </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
            </td></tr></table>
          </ol>
</font></td></tr></table><div style="height: 14px;"></div>        <table width="50" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr>
        <td style="border-top: 1px solid #aaa;"><img src="../img/blank.gif" width="1" height="5"/></td>
        </tr></table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr><td>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#888888><small>
          <ol>
          <li>
The desired standard (MIL-188C or RS232) is selected with a
  <a href="#conf_v24"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Jump to: wire strap at the centre of the ...">wire strap at the centre of the upper PCB</span></a>.
          </li>
          <li>
Adjustable between 20 mA and 60 mA.
          </ol>
          </small></font></td></tr>
        </table>
<div style="height: 20px;"></div>        <div style="height: 18px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc;"></div>
        <a name=conn_nf1></a>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+0" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          Audio input 1 
          &nbsp;<font color="#CCC">
          NF 1
          </font>
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The TG-1001M can handle two receivers, which is particularly useful
when using <b>receiver diversity</b>. Each receiver can be connected via the
audio input (<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Normal Frequenz (Audio Frequency, AF)">NF</span>) or the intermediate frequency input (<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Zwitchen Frequenz (Intermediate Frequency, IF)">ZF</span>).
These two inputs are mutually exclusive. The desired input is selected
&mdash; along with the baudrate &mdash; with <a href="#conf_s1"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Jump to: selector ...">selector <b>S1</b></span></a> at the top
of the device. Below is the pinout of Audio Input 1 (NF1), when looking
into the <a href="../../../ref/conn/din/index.htm#din_45322"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: 6-pin 240&#176; DIN socket">6-pin 240&#176; DIN socket</span></a>.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
